<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Lighter Path<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.80)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12717'>Mark "MerryMark" Dobranski</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12717&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> October 10, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">                    The Lighter Path<br>
<br>
<br>
     Managing the twilight pool is an important and fun part of the Lord of the Rings CCG. The game&#8217;s designers have provided cards that specifically reduce a site&#8217;s shadow number as well as other cards which do not add twilight when played. I&#8217;ll call the latter cards &#8220;free&#8221; cards.  When studying the cards in the Fellowship of the Ring block and the soon to be released Two Towers set it is worth noting the free cards. Only a few of the cards in the Fellowship of the Ring block have both characteristics (reduce a sites shadow number and are free), Bill the Pony and No Strangers to the Shadows. Both of these cards make in into a large percentage of the most competitive decks. This brief article is a quick reference for the serious tournament player making those final, but key card slot decisions &#8211; known as tweaking a deck. Managing twilight falls chiefly on the designing of the Free Peoples half of the deck. <br>
<br>
    There are currently 5 cultures available in the Free Peoples side, Dwarvin, Elven, Gandalf, Gondor, and Shire. But only two of the five cultures have a preponderance of these &#8220;free&#8221; cards that control (do not add to it or even reduce it) the twilight pool when played.  The Gondor and Shire Cultures (Men and Hobbits) have the majority of the cards.  Combined they have 35 of the 55 notable free cards or 64% of the cards. And the two most notable (above paragraph) perhaps, are also from these two cultures. Bill the Pony is part of the Shire culture and No Strangers to the Shadows is part of the Gondor culture.  A breakdown by set and culture will be provided at the end of the article. It can be used as a handy study reference. <br>
<br>
    Tournament players are very keen on quickly detecting their opponent&#8217;s strategy. One element they pay careful attention to is how severely a deck restricts twilight. Five, maybe six aspects of an opponent&#8217;s deck relay this vital information.  First is the choice of cultures that get the deck&#8217;s focus. Obviously, a player with a lot of Gondor or Hobbit companions may be attempting to restrict twilight to help them run. Secondly, the size of the fellowship indicates if a player is severely restricting twilight. A player will generally play no more than 4 companions even though they may have more in their deck. The extra companions, if played, generally are played at site 6 or 7 only in order to be able to handle swarming minions. Third, if many of the cards your opponent plays during their fellowship phase or during skirmishes are free cards this is an obvious indicator.  The fourth aspect a player looks for is if one or even both of the notable free cards are being used &#8211; Bill the Pony is played on a hobbit and No Strangers to the Shadows is played on a Ranger. Fifth, the choice of sites played is an indicator that a player&#8217;s deck is built to restrict twilight, especially if a player does prefer to move second at the start of the game. Sites will be discussed in an independent paragraph.  And a sixth indicator is if one, two or even all three of the following key companions are a part of the deck, Gimli, Dwarf of the Mountain Race (reduces twilight at underground sites, sites 4 and 5), A Ranger (Aragorn, Arwen, Boromir, but especially Aragorn, Heir to the White City) and Pippin, Mr. Took (reduces twilight cost of other characters). The above elements are worth considering when designing your deck and help you identify the type of deck you opponent is playing.<br>
    Thus far I have suggested that a deck that severely restricts twilight generally is designed to run or probably should have been. A deck that is restricting twilight is not only enabling it to run rapidly to site 9, but just as important, a limited twilight pool restricts how deep the opponent draws into his or her deck. When your opponent&#8217;s draw depth is severely restricted he or she is forced to make important choices over small matters, such as what card do I play or which card to discard in order to draw a new card, especially since drawing new cards (getting deeper into their deck) is essentially controlled by the size of the deck. A witch-king discarded at site 3 during regroup, for example, may turn out to be a critical decision because one may not draw into another  <br>
 Powerful minion. To get deeper into their deck a player facing a restrictive twilight strategy will be prompted to play more of their fellowship cards instead in order to be able to draw new cards. <br>
<br>
     Before presenting a list of notable free cards broken down by culture I will discuss site selection. Currently, there are 14 notable sites that provide the least twilight. The first three I&#8217;ll present are perhaps the most important because they help your <br>
Fellowship run to site 4 with little damage taken. West Farthing, Breeland Forest, and Council Courtyard in some capacity limit how much twilight your opponent has to play his Shadow cards. Council Courtyard is seen the most.<br>
 <br>
<br>
Gondor (17)<br>
<br>
Fellowship of the Ring<br>
  No Stranger to the Shadows<br>
  Path Finder<br>
  Swordsman of the Northern Kingdom<br>
  Swordarm of the White Tower<br>
  Strength of Kings<br>
Mines of Moria<br>
  Flaming Brand<br>
  Gondor will see it done<br>
  No Mere Ranger<br>
  Sentinels of Numenor<br>
Realms of the Elf-lords<br>
  Answering the Cries<br>
  Aragorn Heir to the White City<br>
  Banner of the White Tree<br>
  Gondor Bowmen<br>
  Some Who Resisted<br>
  Still Sharp (played with Shards of Narsill)<br>
  Voice of Rauros<br>
  We Must Go Warily<br>
